1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,459
Ever wondered how to supercharge your data science workflow with AI agents directly in VS Code?

2
00:00:07,120 --> 00:00:11,439
Today, I'll walk you through installing the Hyper Velocity Engineering Extension

3
00:00:11,439 --> 00:00:17,640
and using its AI native agents to load, explore, and model the Titanic data set

4
00:00:17,640 --> 00:00:26,519
without writing any code yourself. Let's start by installing the Hyper Velocity Engineering,

5
00:00:26,519 --> 00:00:35,280
or HVE extension in VS Code. Click the extensions icon on the left sidebar. It looks like four squares.

6
00:00:35,880 --> 00:00:41,780
In the search bar that pops up, type Hyper Velocity Engineering. When you see it in the list,

7
00:00:42,100 --> 00:00:47,539
click the blue install button. That's it. No need for any API keys or credentials.

8
00:00:50,799 --> 00:00:57,340
Now, let's explore the agents HVE adds to VS Code. Click the co-pilot chat icon.

9
00:00:57,340 --> 00:01:01,179
It looks like a speech bubble in the sidebar. A chat panel will open.

10
00:01:01,700 --> 00:01:05,079
In the agent picker at the top, you'll notice several agent options,

11
00:01:05,519 --> 00:01:11,920
including at-task researcher, at-task planner, and at-task implementer. These are your AI partners

12
00:01:11,920 --> 00:01:17,280
for end-to-end data science tasks. We'll use them step by step to work with the Titanic data.

13
00:01:20,379 --> 00:01:25,420
First, let's research the Titanic data set. In the co-pilot chat panel,

14
00:01:25,420 --> 00:01:32,980
select at-task researcher from the agent picker. Type explore-titanic.csv and summarize the data.

15
00:01:33,459 --> 00:01:39,280
Hit enter. The agent will create a research markdown file. To see the output, look in the explorer.

16
00:01:39,900 --> 00:01:45,180
You'll find a new .co-pilot tracking slash research folder with a markdown file inside.

17
00:01:45,640 --> 00:01:54,090
Open it to review the automated analysis. Next, let's plan the actual analysis.

18
00:01:54,650 --> 00:01:58,250
In the co-pilot chat panel, switch to at-task planner.

19
00:01:58,989 --> 00:02:05,870
Type plan a Python script to load, explore, and predict survival on Titanic.csv.

20
00:02:06,530 --> 00:02:11,870
The planner agent will create a plan file in the .co-pilot tracking plans folder.

21
00:02:12,490 --> 00:02:17,210
Check the explorer for this new plan. Open it to read through the detailed steps

22
00:02:17,210 --> 00:02:20,169
the agent has devised for our data science workflow.

23
00:02:23,110 --> 00:02:29,229
It's time to bring it all together. Select at-task implementer in the co-pilot chat agent picker.

24
00:02:29,590 --> 00:02:33,750
Prompt it. Implement the plan for titanic.csv analysis in Python.

25
00:02:34,650 --> 00:02:38,189
The agent generates the complete script. No copy pasting required.

26
00:02:38,930 --> 00:02:43,289
Check the .co-pilot tracking details folder for the implementation details file.

27
00:02:43,889 --> 00:02:46,669
Open the file to see the ready to run Python code.

28
00:02:47,229 --> 00:02:49,509
Double-click the script to open it in the editor.

29
00:02:49,979 --> 00:02:53,090
Then click the run Python file button at the top right of the editor.

30
00:02:53,550 --> 00:02:59,349
The terminal will display the output, likely some basic EDA and survival predictions using the Titanic

31
00:02:59,349 --> 00:03:04,030
data. This all happens automatically thanks to HVE's agent workflow.

32
00:03:06,919 --> 00:03:13,180
We installed HVE core, explored its agents, and walked step by step through researching,

33
00:03:13,500 --> 00:03:18,180
planning, and implementing a data science workflow on the Titanic dataset.

34
00:03:18,659 --> 00:03:22,939
All seamlessly inside VS code using AI agents.

35
00:03:26,219 --> 00:03:30,419
Try out the hyper-velocity engineering extension in your own projects

36
00:03:30,879 --> 00:03:37,159
and experiment with the other agents like at-rpi agent to speed up more complex workflows.

